Prime Minister Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwesaid he suspended key talks to unite his ruling ZANU-PF partyand opposition PF-ZAPU party.    "I am sorry to say we have been deadlocked for too long onthe question of unity, and the central committee of my partyhas recently decided that the talks be discontinued for theyare serving no purpose," he said in a nationwideradio-and-television address.    The collapse of the unity talks, widely expected to haveheralded creation of a socialist, one-party state, was a majorsetback for the government, diplomats said. Reuter&#3;